			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2011</a> paper:</span><br><i>RLSRunner: Linking Rascal with K for Program Analysis</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/MarkHills.html">Mark Hills</a>, <a href="../profile/PaulKlint.html">Paul Klint</a>, <a href="../profile/JurgenVinju.html">Jurgen Vinju</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-28830-2_19">10.1007/978-3-642-28830-2_19</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> RLSRunner is a tool that integrates Rascal with K-based analyzers, functioning as a meta-tool/workbench component.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> Both Rascal and K are meta-languages used to specify analyses and semantics.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> The purpose of the integration is program analysis driven by language definitions and semantics.
</li></ul></li></ul>
